Data preparation¶

Before doing any analysis, we'll neeed to get the data arranged. First load the dataframe and pull out the reviews for the hotel property we're interested in. For demo purposes, I'll just look at sub-sample of the reviews (to save processing time). You should use a larger sample or, ideally, the full set of reviews for your hotel.

In [3]:
df = pd.read_parquet("../lab-02/hotel_review.parquet")
df['review_text'] = df['title'] + " " + df['text']
hotel = df.query('offering_id == 93520').sample(500, random_state=42)

Next we'll divide the reviews into sentences using spacy's sentencizer module. We also want to keep track of which review each sentences came from and what the overall rating was (for later analysis). By default, the spacy pipe function takes strings and produces spacy docs:

text -> metadata

If we set the as_tuples option, though, it pipe expects pairs of a string and some arbirtary metadata and it produces pairs of spacy docs and metadata. We'll want to keep track of two pieces of metadata--which review the sentence came from and what that review's star rating was--so we've got:

(text, (review_id, rating)) -> (doc, (review_id, rating))
In [4]:
sentence_splitter = spacy.blank("en")
sentence_splitter.add_pipe("sentencizer")

docs_with_metadata = (
    (row.review_text, (row.Index, row.overall))
    for row in hotel[["review_text", "overall"]].itertuples()
)

sents = pd.DataFrame(
    {"text": s.orth_, "review_id": id, "rating": overall}
    for doc, (id, overall) in sentence_splitter.pipe(docs_with_metadata, as_tuples=True)
    for s in doc.sents
)

The results is a dataframe the lists the text of individual sentences, the index value of the review they came from, and the overall star rating associated with the review:

Vectorization¶

Before we can cluster sentences, we first need to convert them vectors the reflect their meaning, with the goal that cosine similarity between the vectors correlates with semantic similarity. We'll try three methods: Latent Semantic Analysis, static embeddings (GloVe vectors), and sentence transformers (SBERT).

Latent semantic analysis¶

One of the earliest methods for constructing semantic vectors, LSA uses Principal Components Analysis to find a low-dimensional representation for the document-term matrix. Actually, we'll technically cheat a bit by skipping the preprocessing steps that are part of PCA and just use the fast and efficient SVD.

For more details about this, see:

  • scikit-learn user's guide
  • Müller & Guido sections 3.4.1 and 7.5
  • Albrecht et al chapters 5 and 10.
In [7]:
mwt = spacy.load('../lab-02/mwt')
sents['tokenized'] = [[t.norm_ for t in doc if not t.is_space] for doc in mwt.pipe(tqdm(sents['text']))]

  0%|          | 0/4210 [00:00<?, ?it/s]

First step is to construct the document-term matrix. Setting analyzer=identity disables TfidfVectorizer's internal tokenizer. TfidfVectorizer has lots of flags you can set to change its behavior. You might try playing with the values of min_df, max_df, use_idf, smooth_idf, sublinear_tf, and binary.

The only parameter for TruncatedSVD is n_components. This determines the number of latent semantic dimensions in our final result.

In [8]:
NDIM = 25

vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(analyzer=identity)
dtm = vectorizer.fit_transform(sents['tokenized'])
lsa_vectors = TruncatedSVD(n_components=NDIM).fit_transform(dtm)
lsa_vectors.shape
Out[8]:
(4210, 25)

Static embeddings¶

Here we'll use spacy's fasttext vectors which are distributed as part of the en_core_web_lg model. For this kind of model, all the important choices are made when the vectors are trained so we don't have any control over them beyond choosing which set of vectors to use. The vectors included with spacy are based on general English text and are approriate for a lot of applications. If we were working with a specialized genre (e.g., scientific articles) we could use (or build) a set of vectors for that specific application. For now, we'll stick with the defaults.

See Albrecht et al chapter 10 for more.

In [9]:
nlp = spacy.load(
    "en_core_web_lg",
    exclude=["attribute_ruler", "tagger", "parser", "lemmatizer", "ner"],
)
In [10]:
full_spacy_vectors = np.array([s.vector for s in nlp.pipe(tqdm(sents['text']))])
full_spacy_vectors.shape

  0%|          | 0/4210 [00:00<?, ?it/s]
Out[10]:
(4210, 300)

Spacy's vectors have 300 dimensions. This is way more than we need to capture patterns in only ~4,000 sentences and their large size will make the nexts steps much more expensive. So before continuing, we'll use TruncatedSVD again to reduce them down to the same number of dimensions we used for LSA up above:

In [11]:
spacy_vectors = TruncatedSVD(n_components=NDIM).fit_transform(full_spacy_vectors)
spacy_vectors.shape
Out[11]:
(4210, 25)

Contextual embeddings¶

Static embeddings always map a word to the same vector regardless of how it's being used in a sentence. Contextual embeddings on the other hand take sentence context into account. We'll use one of the SBERT models, which are transformers trained specifically for computing semantic distance between sentences.

Like static embeddings, all the of the choices for contextual embeddings are made at the time the model is constructed. The only choice we can make is selecting which model to use. There is a list of SBERT models here. We'll start with all-mpnet-base-v2. This is very large model that has shown good average performance on a range of semantic similarity tasks. Note that that's average performance. Other models might work better on this particular task and might be worth a try. Also consider using one of the multilingual models which can measure semantic similarity between sentences across different languages.

Chapter 1 in Tunstall et al gives some general background on BERT-type transformers. SBERT models are transformers that are trained on human ratings of semantic similarity between short texts.

In [12]:
model = SentenceTransformer("all-mpnet-base-v2")

full_sbert_vectors = model.encode(sents['text'])
full_sbert_vectors.shape

And just as we did for the static embeddings, we'll reduce our SBERT embeddings from 768 dimensions down to 25:

In [14]:

sbert_vectors.shape
Out[14]:

Clusters¶

Now that we have a way of computing semantic distances, the next step in our analysis is to look for patterns in groups of sentences that express similar meanings. We'll combine two methods: t-SNE and HDBSCAN.

t-SNE¶

T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding or t-SNE is a manifold learning algorithm which maps high-dimensional data into a very low-dimensional space (typically 2 or 3 dimensions to allow visualization of patterns).

As you can guess, TSNE has a number of hyperparameters that effect its behavior. The most important (besides n_components of course) is perplexity. The effect this has depends a lot on the particulars of your dataset, slo you'll have to try different values to see what works best for you.

For more about how t-SNE works and how to interpret the results see:

  • scikit-learn user's guide
  • How to Use t-SNE Effectively
  • Müller & Guido section 3.4.3
  • Albrecht et al chapter 10

The primary use of t-SNE is to visualize patterns, so we'll define a function to plot a 2d projection of review data. Color shading reflects ratings: blue dots have 5 stars and red dots have 1 star.

In [15]:
def plot_projection(proj, title=None):
    plt.scatter(
        proj[:, 0], proj[:, 1], s=3, alpha=0.3, c=sents["rating"], cmap=cc.m_CET_D8_r
    )
    plt.tick_params(left=False, bottom=False, labelleft=False, labelbottom=False)
    if title:
        plt.title(title)

First let's compare our three different vectorization methods. We can see that t-SNE is able to find structure in all three sets of vectors, but the SBERT vectors have the most structure and also best separate positive and negative comments.

In [16]:
plot_projection(TSNE(2, perplexity=25).fit_transform(lsa_vectors), title="LSA")
plt.show()
plot_projection(TSNE(2, perplexity=25).fit_transform(spacy_vectors), title="spacy")
plt.show()
plot_projection(TSNE(2, perplexity=25).fit_transform(sbert_vectors), title="SBERT")
plt.show()

Next let's compare the results for SBERT vectors with different values for perlexity. Which looks most informative?

In [17]:

plt.show()

HDBSCAN¶

We can see some patterns in the data just by eyeballing 2d or 3d t-SNE plots, but we can find more subtle patterns by applying a clustering method to the data in higher dimensions. For semantic vectors, the hierarchical density-based clustering algorithm HDBSCAN has been shown to give good results.

HBDSCAN has a few important hyperparameters: the most important is probably min_cluster_size, which sets the bottom limit for how small a cluster can be and still count as a cluster.

See also:

  • scikit-learn user's guide
  • Müller & Guido section 3.5.3
In [19]:
clusters = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=10).fit_predict(sbert_vectors)

Looking at the number of sentences in each cluster gives us one measure of what the algorithm has found. In this case, there are 13 clusters numbered 0-12. Sentences which didn't get put in any cluster get the label -1 and are considered noise.

In [20]:
print(Counter(clusters))

Counter({-1: 3180, 3: 323, 8: 214, 10: 110, 7: 94, 6: 62, 4: 59, 5: 55, 1: 51, 0: 19, 9: 16, 2: 15, 11: 12})

Another way to evaluate the results is to re-draw our t-SNE plot using color-coded clusters rather then star ratings

In [21]:
def plot_clusters(proj, clusters, title=None):
    alpha = [0.02 if c == -1 else 1.0 for c in clusters]
    plt.scatter(proj[:, 0], proj[:, 1], s=3, alpha=alpha, c=clusters, cmap=cc.m_glasbey)
    plt.tick_params(left=False, bottom=False, labelleft=False, labelbottom=False)
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
In [22]:
plot_clusters(projection, clusters)

Once we have a clustering solution we like, add it to our sentences.

In [23]:
sents['cluster'] = clusters

Interpretation¶

Now we have to somehow make sense of all this!

Cluster keywords¶

To assign interpretions or labels to clusters, we can use keyword analysis to find words that are frequent in sentences in a cluster and/or that are associated with a cluster.

Start with freqeuncy:

In [24]:
for c in sorted(sents['cluster'].unique()):
    if c != -1:
        freq = Counter(concat(sents.query(f'cluster=={c}')['tokenized']))
        print(c, ' '.join(f'{w} ({f})' for w,f in freq.most_common(5)))

In [25]:
vocab = Counter(concat(sents['tokenized']))

for c in sorted(sents['cluster'].unique()):
    if c != -1:
        freq = Counter(concat(sents.query(f'cluster=={c}')['tokenized']))
        mi = Counter()
        for w in freq:
            if freq[w] > 5:
                mi[w] = (np.log2(freq[w]) + np.log2(vocab.total()) 
                         - np.log2(vocab[w]) - np.log2(freq.total()))       
        print(c, ' '.join(f'{w} ({f:5.3})' for w,f in mi.most_common(5)))

Topics¶

Another approach (used by BERTopic) treats sentence cluster labels a bit like the topics produced by LDA. They can then be analyzed using any of the methods you might use for interpreting the results of an LDA model.

For one, we can look at how clusters correlate with overall ratings. We can see that clusters 5, 6, and 9 show up a lot in negative reviews.

Interactive exploration¶

The last method we'll consider uses Bokeh to create an interative visualization.

In [30]:
tooltips = [("text", "@sent")]
tooltips = """
<div style="width:400px;margin: 0px 0px 5px 0px;">@rating★ "@text"</div>

palette = list(reversed(cc.CET_D8))
rating_cmap = linear_cmap("rating", palette=palette, low=1, high=5)

p = figure(
    x_axis_type=None,
    y_axis_type=None,
    tools="pan,wheel_zoom,box_zoom,zoom_in,zoom_out,hover,save,reset,help",
    tooltips=tooltips,
    title="Ratings"
)
scatter = p.scatter(
    "x",
    "y",
    source=sents,
    fill_alpha=0.8,
    alpha=0.01,
    radius=0.6,
    fill_color=rating_cmap,
)

show(p)

tooltips = [("text", "@sent")]
tooltips = """
<div style="width:400px;margin: 0px 0px 5px 0px;">@rating★ (@cluster) "@text"</div>
"""

cmap = linear_cmap("cluster", palette=cc.glasbey, low=0, high=sents['cluster'].max())

p = figure(
    x_axis_type=None,
    y_axis_type=None,
    tools="pan,wheel_zoom,box_zoom,zoom_in,zoom_out,hover,save,reset,help",
    tooltips=tooltips,
    title="Clusters"
)
p.scatter(
    "x",
    "y",
    source=sents.query('cluster!=-1'),
    fill_alpha=0.8,
    alpha=0.01,
    radius=0.6,
    fill_color=cmap,
)
show(p)
